  					<td align=center valign="top" width=100%><br>
  						<!--#beginContent#-->
  						<table align='center' cellpadding=5 width='85%'>  <tr><td class='spti2' width='100%'>PLAYER STRATEGY - CLERIC</td></tr>  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'><font class='dbti'>HIGH ELF CLERIC 1-6</font> - <small>Gwena of Tholuxe Paells, Tholuxe Paells</td></tr>
  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'>
<p>This is not a real good Power Level strategy, but it will help make your character in the areas to build up skills and level with reasonable safety.<br>
<br>
First off, definitely memorize your first level spells, Minor Healing and Courage.  It is a long process, and will be until 8th Level for your spells.<br>
<br>
Go to the Cleric's guild and give them your note, wear the armor and train in the following: 1HB, 2HB, Alteration and Aburation.  The last one, I recommend in Tailoring or Bind Wounds or Heading Sense.<br>
<br>
Now hit the road, taking the right, then left, left forks to Kelethin.  Reason: Better viewable newbie zone for your High Elf.  Concentrate on Bats for your first level fighting. stay near the lift or people area so that if you get jumped by an Orc, you can get someone to pull it off you.<br>
<br>
When you have the mana to spare, cast Courage and Minor healing on other players as much as possible.  Reason: Build up skill in Alteration and Aburation and less chance of fizzles later on when you need to shoot off those spells.  Sit near the guards when getting your mana up, less chance of a stray orc or wolf hitting you.<br>
<br>
When you reach Level 2, don't return yet.  Start hitting Wolves and Skeletons.  Definitely hit skeletons with Rusty weapons, eventually, you will find one with a rusty mace or a staff.  I recommend wolves first, mostly because they provide wolf pelts you can ask around for people to help make patchwork armor for your character.  Skeletons are good for getting the 4 bone chips you need to get the strike spell which will come in handy later.  When you are ready to go back to Cleric Guild with more money to purchase spells, Train 1 point into Evocation, divination, and conjuration.  Dedicate the other 2 points to anything, although I recommend into tailoring once again.<br>
<br>
Now, once you get to third level, start hitting orc pawns, pixies and anything that still cons blue.  Hopefully, you will have some PW armor by now, because Orcs and armed Pixies hurt a bit more until you get some armor, then it won't hurt as much unless the orcs are armed with 2HS weapons.  You might want to start watching your HB skills, switching weapons to build up the other so that you will be able to hit reasonably with either weapon.  You should keep doing this in Level 4 as well, with a minor recommendation of working on tailoring skills on Hatchling silks.  Reason for Tailoring: Even if you have full PW armor, your High Wis and Int will allow you to become a Newbie's friend, make bandages, come in handy for later armor items.  If you don't have full PW armor, it gives you a chance to try and make some yourself.<br>
<br>
Once you reach 5th level, you are stuck with only 3 mobs in the Newbie area you can hunt for XP, Orc Pawns, Pixies and Hatchlings.  While it is tediously slow to do so, it does allow one thing, skill buildup to max.  The problem with power leveling without the skills to match == more chances of you dying or spell fizzling, because your abilities are too weak.  It also means less time to build up your skills so they work better in the long run.  You can keep doing this til you get to Level 6, by then, they will be all green and you can move onto the Orc Lift Area.<br>
<br>
At Level 6, you can, with in reason, solo some of the Orc Cents, Blue or Even ones.  You won't have problems with Orc Pawns, since they are green and will avoid hitting you unless you hit them.  They are also good for building up your skills and working on timing.<br>
</p>
</td></tr>
  <tr><td class='db'>&nbsp;</td></tr>
